i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 The appellant in each of these appeals is the}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li6077\fi0\ri0\sb389\sa0\tldot\tx9166 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 /Johannesburg{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn1433\margrsxn497\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li36\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 2}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li36\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Johannesburg firm of attorneys, Messrs Joel Melamed and Hurwitz}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb7\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 ("Melamed and Hurwitz"). At all material times the senior partner in the firm was Mr Joel Melamed. As at the time of the trial (ie August 1981) he had been practising as an attor\-ney in Johannesburg for some 34 years. For some time prior to the events with which these appeals are concerned Melamed and his partner, Mr S Hurwitz, had been interested in township develop\-ment. They held financial interests in certain townships which were in the process of being established and exploited; and in addition they, together with one Simmons, formed and operated a company, Township Management Consultants (Pty) Ltd ("TMC"), which, as its name indicates, was incorporated to carry on the business of establishing and managing townships and marketing the erven therein on behalf of the township owners. Melamed, Hurwitz and Simmons had equal shareholdings in TMC and Melamed was its managing director.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li1505\fi0\ri0\sb490\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 In approximately 1961 Melamed met Mr Harry Galaun.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li6106\fi0\ri0\sb468\sa0\tldot\tx8734 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 /Galaun{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn1498\margrsxn425\margtsxn1440\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li8662\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 3}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb317\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 Galaun became a client of Melamed's. Together, they went into a small business venture, the details of which are unimportant. In due course they became personal friends. Through two com\-panies, Cleveland Estates (Pty) Ltd ("Cleveland"), respondent in the first appeal, and Vorner Investments (Pty) Ltd ("Vomer") , respondent in the second appeal, Galaun was interested in certain land, which in Melamed's opinion was suitable for township develop\-ment. Cleveland had owned a property near Halfway House for many years. Galaun had tried to establish an agricultural holdings township on the property, but without success. Galaun sought Melamed's advice as to what could be done with the land. After investigating the position, Melamed advised Galaun that the property would make an excellent residential dormitory township. Melamed suggested that a township, to be known as Vorna Valley Township, be established and that TMC be appointed the township manager. This was agreed to and in December 1968 Cleveland and TMC entered into a written agreement in terms whereof TMC}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li6098\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-720\slmult0\tldot\tx9029 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 /undertook{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn1473\margrsxn608\margtsxn1440\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li8662\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 4}\par \pard \plain \cbpa