s22 documents needed for the establishment of the township}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li22\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 and authorises the management company to act as its agent}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li14\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 to enter into contracts necessary for the reticulation of the}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li14\fi0\ri0\sb7\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 township. The contract further provides that the township}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li14\fi0\ri0\sb7\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 owner appoints the management company as its sole agent}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 for the sale of all stands in the township. In return for its}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li14\fi0\ri0\sb14\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 services the management company is to be paid a commission}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7\fi0\ri0\sb7\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 of six per centum on gross sales in respect of all sales}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7\fi0\ri0\sb14\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 effected and a management fee of five per centum of the}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 gross amount received from the sales of all stands in the}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li14\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 township. Clause 8(a) of the contract reads as follows:}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5350\fi0\ri0\sb684\sa0\tldot\tx7978 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 / "The{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2304\margrsxn813\margtsxn936\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7920\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 6}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2513\fi-115\ri0\sb612\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 "The Township Owner agrees that the Manage\-ment Company shall have the right to ap\-point Attorneys, Auditors, Surveyors, Agents and Auctioneers to act on behalf of the Township Owner in all matters re\-lating to the establishment of the Township, transfer of stands in the Township, any application to court, or any matters in connection with or appertaining to the establishment of the township;...."}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1318\ri0\sb331\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Thereafter TMC proceeded to take the necessary steps to have the two townships established. At that time erven in a township could be sold to the public before the proclamation of the township, provided that the township owner had furnished certain guarantees. This was done, and an advertising and selling programme was prepared. In May 1971 the stage had been reached when the erven in the two townships were ready for sale. TMC arranged for the printing of the necessary \ul pro forma\ul0  deeds of sale. Several thousand such \ul pro forma\ul0  deeds were printed. The deeds for the two townships differ somewhat in form, but each contains, in the relative clause governing the passing of transfer, a provision to the effect that transfer shall}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5350\fi0\ri0\sb7\sa0\sl-720\slmult0\tldot\tx7985 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw41\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 /be\expndtw0 {\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2193\margrsxn659\margtsxn1167\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7963\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 7}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li36\fi0\ri0\sb331\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 be passed to the purchaser by the seller's conveyancers, who in the one instance (the Cleveland contract) are stated to be Joel Melamed and Hurwitz and in the other (the Vorner contract) as Joel Melamed, Hurwitz and Seligson. It is common cause that, despite the difference in the name, the appellant is the conveyancer nominated in each of the contracts.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1346\ri0\sb245\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 For the next ten years the establishment and management of the townships and the sale of erven therein proceeded in accordance with the management contract. After the townships had been proclaimed (in the case of Unitas Park this was in 1973 and 1977 in the case of Vorna Valley) the erven which had been sold and paid for were transferred to the purchasers thereof. Galaun, on behalf of either Cleveland or Vorner, as the case may be, signed each deed of sale. His practice was to visit TMC's offices four days a week in order to attend to this business. According to Melamed, he and Galaun would discuss each sale}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5357\fi0\ri0\sb367\sa0\tldot\tx8590 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 / and{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2262\margrsxn410\margtsxn1440\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7942\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 8}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li36\fi0\ri0\sb331\sa0\sl-720\slmult0\tx2491 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 and the business\loch\f12\cchs0 {\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }\loch\f0\cchs0 of the townships in general on the occasion\line of these visits. When the time came for an erf to be}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li22\fi0\ri864\sb0\sa0\sl-720\slmult0\tx2491 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 transferred, TMC\loch\f12\cchs0 {\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }\loch\f0\cchs0 would instruct Melamed and Hurwitz to\line pass transfer.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1325\ri0\sb245\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Suddenly, in mid-1979, both Cleveland and Vorner terminated TMC's appointment as management company. Melamed attributed this to "progressive senility" on the part of Galaun, who in May 1979 "suddenly decided that he didn't like me (Melamed) because he said I was doing too much work for another client by the name of Hymie Tucker and I was not attending to his work". Early in June a dispute arose between Cleveland and Vorner, on the one hand, and TMC, on the other, in regard to the latter's claims in respect of management fees and commissions; and on 29 June 1979 the auditors to Cleveland and Vorner, Messrs Goldstuck Herscovitz and Company ("the auditors"), addressed a letter to TMC, the concluding paragraphs of which read as follows:}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5357\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-720\slmult0\tldot\tx8446 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 / "Our{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2215\margrsxn752\margtsxn914\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7949\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 9}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2549\fi-137\ri0\sb619\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 "Our clients, in any event, wish to terminate your appointment as manage\-ment company with effect from the 31st day of July 1979, and on that date we shall be pleased if you will kindly have all books, records and documents available for collection by our clients or their representatives.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2549\fi0\ri864\sb252\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Our clients similarly terminate your employment as the sole selling agent with effect from the same date."}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1325\ri0\sb331\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 This letter came as something of a bombshell. It elicited replies from both Melamed and Hurwitz and TMC. On 4 July 1979 Melamed and Hurwitz addressed to the auditors two letters, one in respect of the management contract with Cleveland and one in respect of the management contract with Vomer. They are substantially in identical terms. The one to Cleveland reads as follows:}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2513\fi-151\ri0\sb533\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 "In terms of a management contract entered into by Cleveland Estates (Pty) Limited and Township Management Consultants (Pty) Limited we were appointed as the Attorneys to attend to all transfers in the township of Vorner Valley. The benefits flowing from the said contract were accepted by us and we have been attending to the trans\-fers of erven under this contract."}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5357\fi0\ri0\sb461\sa0\tldot\tx8741 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 /The{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2179\margrsxn1055\margtsxn1102\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7992\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-2\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 10}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li36\fi0\ri0\sb324\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 The auditors responded to these letters by a letter dated 10 July 1979 asking for information in regard to Melamed and Hurwitz's appointment as attorneys: whether it was in writing and, if so, a copy thereof; if verbal, then various details of the appointment. Melamed and Hurwitz replied on 24 July 1979 stating \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f1\cchs0 \'97}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2405\fi-137\ri432\sb540\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 "Our appointment was in terms of Clause 8 of the management contract. The appointment was confirmed on numerous occasions by Mr H Galaun acting on be-half of Cleveland Estates (Pty) Limited and Vorner Investments (Pty) Limited."}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li36\fi0\ri0\sb691\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 and refusing further details.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1332\ri0\sb338\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Melamed and Hurwitz addressed a further letter to the auditors on 23 July 1979, but here they were evidently acting on behalf of TMC. The letter recounts the history of the management contracts and states, \ul inter alia\ul0 , that "in regard to the purported cancellation of the management contracts we would point out that our appoint\-ment is an irrevocable appointment....". The letter also}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5378\fi0\ri0\sb396\sa0\tldot\tx8467 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 /purports{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2045\margrsxn360\margtsxn864\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li8093\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-10\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 11}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li14\fi0\ri2016\sb194\sa0\sl-727\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 purports to terminate the appointment of Goldstuck Herscoviz & Co as auditors to the companies.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1181\ri0\sb223\sa0\sl-727\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 On 29 August 1979 attorneys acting on behalf of Cleveland and Vomer addressed a long letter to Melamed and Hurwitz dealing with the management fees and sales commissions claimed by TMC and "the appointment of your\-selves as the conveyancers to attend to the transfer of the stands". In the letter the view is expressed that TMC's appointment under the management contract is not irrevocable and that, if the companies acted incorrectly in cancelling the appointment, the only remedy is one in damages. In regard to the appointment of Melamed and Hurwitz as con\-veyancers, claimed also to be irrevocable, the letter says that such an irrevocable appointment is for certain (stated) reasons not enforceable and that consequently the companies were entitled to cancel "the purported irrevocable appointment". The letter also contains a demand that Melamed & Hurwitz hand over the books and documents relating to the management of the companies, which this firm was apparently refusing to do.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5184\fi0\ri0\sb346\sa0\tldot\tx8273 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Melamed{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2215\margrsxn1040\margtsxn1440\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7956\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-6\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 12}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li36\fi0\ri0\sb317\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Melamed and Hurwitz replied to this letter on 6 September 1979 stating, \ul inter alia\ul0  \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f1\cchs0 \'97}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2534\fi-130\ri432\sb533\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 "We again note your advice in regard to our irrevocable appointment as Convey\-ancers. Your advice is not based on the correct facts. Mr Galaun was a party to our irrevocable appointment as Conveyancers. In any event only our client has the right to terminate our mandate".}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1325\ri0\sb324\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 These various disputes between the parties led to Cleveland and Vomer on 9 October 1979 instituting motion proceedings in the Witwatersrand Local Division, citing TMC and Melamed and Hurwitz as respondents and claiming an order declaring TMC's appointment under the management contracts and Melamed and Hurwitz's appointment as con\-veyancers to have been effectively terminated, directing TMC to return to the companies their books, documents and records and making certain declarations in regard to management fees and commissions. The matter came before}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5364\fi0\ri0\sb7\sa0\sl-720\slmult0\tldot\tx8460 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 / LE GRANGE J {\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2153\margrsxn360\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li8100\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-6\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 13}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb317\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 LE GRANGE J on 3 March 1980. The learned Judge concluded that Cleveland and Vomer were entitled to revoke the appointments contained in the management contracts; and that, as it was common cause that the fate of the appointment of Melamed and Hurwitz as conveyancers followed the fate of the management contracts, the companies were entitled to terminate the appointment of Melamed and Hurwitz. An appeal against this judgment was noted but not prosecuted.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1339\ri0\sb238\sa0\sl-727\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 In August 1980 Melamed and Hurwitz instituted separate actions against Cleveland and Vomer in the Witwatersrand Local Division, claiming in each case damages for the un\-lawful cancellation of the appointment of the firm as con\-veyancer. The pleadings in each case are substantially identical, the only differences relating to the number of erven still to be transferred in the township and the amount of damages claimed, which in Cleveland's case was R99 645,00}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5364\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-727\slmult0\tldot\tx8906 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 / (alternatively{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2225\margrsxn742\margtsxn1022\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7949\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-2\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 14}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li29\fi0\ri0\sb331\sa0\sl-727\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 (alternatively R59 160,00) and in Vomer's case R27 790,00 (alternatively R10 645,00). Again, to avoid unnecessary repetition I shall refer, in the main, only to the action against Cleveland.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1332\ri0\sb238\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 For purposes of trial the two actions were consoli\-dated. The matter came before DE VILLIERS J. By agree\-ment between the parties (reached during the trial), it was ordered in terms of Rule of Court 33(4) that the question of liability be decided first and that the further proceedings, ie as to the quantum of damages, be stayed until the question of liability had been disposed of. At the conclusion of the trial the learned trial Judge came to the conclusion that Melamed and Hurwitz had failed to establish a liability for damages on the part of the two companies and in each case the plaintiff's claims were dismissed with costs. On appeal to this Court it is con\-tended on behalf of Melamed and Hurwitz that the trial Judge's finding on the question of liability was erroneous.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5350\fi0\ri0\sb576\sa0\tldot\tx8597 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw27\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs26 /In\expndtw0 {\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2145\margrsxn360\margtsxn1213\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li8129\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-25\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 15}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1332\ri0\sb324\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 In judging the merits of the appeal it is important, in the first place, to see how the partnership, Melamed and Hurwitz, pleaded its cause of action. The particulars of claim refer to the conclusion of the management contract and to the provisions of the contract in terms whereof TMC was appointed as the sole agent of the company (Cleveland) for the sale of all stands in the township which was to be established on Cleveland's property and was given the right (in clause 8) to, \ul inter alia\ul0 , appoint attorneys to act on behalf of Cleveland in all matters relating to the transfer of stands in the township. It is alleged that on a proper construction of the contract TMC was en-titled to appoint conveyancers on the basis that such conveyancers "were retained to effect the transfer of all stands in the said township"; and (in par 4 of the particulars of claim) that in pursuance of clause 8 TMC duly appointed Melamed and Hurwitz as the attorneys to act on behalf of Cleveland, that Melamed and Hurwitz duly accepted the}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5364\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-720\slmult0\tldot\tx8453 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 / appointment{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn1811\margrsxn875\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li8849\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-6\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 16}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li14\fi0\ri295\sb324\sa0\sl-727\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 and that the appointment was, \ul inter alia\ul0 , to act as con\-veyancers for the transfer of all stands in the proposed township. As an alternative to par 4, plaintiff (in par 5)}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb130\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 repeats the contents of par 4 and then proceeds to allege that in or about February/March 1971 and at Johannesburg Cleveland, \expndtw16 acting\expndtw0  through its director, Harry \expndtw12 Galaun, \expndtw0 "orally adopted and/or confirmed and/or ratified the said appointment" and that in the premises an oral contract came into being between the parties in terms whereof Melamed and Hurwitz were appointed to act as conveyancers for the transfer of all stands in the township. The particulars of claim further aver the unlawful cancellation of plaintiff's appointment and the damages sustained as a result of such unlawful cancellation. The claim for damages is based upon the fees that plaintiff would have earned from the conveyancing work involved in transferring stands in}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5796\fi0\ri0\sb7\sa0\sl-720\slmult0\tldot\tx8273 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 / the{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2239\margrsxn886\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\qr\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-12\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 17}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb202\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 the townships had its appointment as conveyancer not been cancelled. It should be noted that the case is not concerned with those instances where prior to the termination of its appointment Melamed and Hurwitz had received specific instructions to pass transfer. It relates only to those stands in the townships which were to be transferred at some undefined time in the future. In addition, a further alternative cause of action, based upon an alleged stipulation for the bene-fit of a third party, is set forth in the particulars of claim (as amended). In this regard it is alleged that in terms of the various deeds of sale entered into with purchasers of erven in the township the firm of Melamed and Hurwitz was appointed as conveyancer to attend to transfer of the property, that this appointment was a stipulation for the benefit of Melamed and Hurwitz and that the latter accepted this benefit. There then}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5350\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-720\slmult0\tldot\tx7978 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 / follows{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2250\margrsxn745\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\qr\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 18}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li29\fi0\ri0\sb302\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 follows an allegation that as a result of the unlawful cancellation of plaintiff's appointment damages (in a lesser sum than in terms of the main claim) were suffered by plaintiff.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1483\ri0\sb259\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 In a request for further particulars to plain\-tiff's particulars of claim, defendant asked a number of questions regarding the appointment of Melamed and Hurwitz as conveyancers by TMC, as alleged in par 4. From the answers furnished it appears that plaintiff alleges that TMC appointed Melamed and Hurwitz "in and during June 1971"; that the appointment was made at the offices of Melamed and Hurwitz; that the appointment was tacit; that Joel Melamed acted both on behalf of TMC, ie in making the appointment, and on behalf of Melamed and Hurwitz, ie in accepting the appointment; and that Joel Melamed, on behalf of Melamed and Hurwitz, conveyed such acceptance}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5350\fi0\ri0\sb374\sa0\tldot\tx8129 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw54\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 /to\expndtw0 {\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2157\margrsxn954\margtsxn1418\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li8410\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-6\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 19}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li22\fi0\ri403\sb310\sa0\sl-713\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 to himself, on behalf of TMC. The request also asked what was unlawful about the cancellation of plaintiff's appointment, to which plaintiff replied that it was unlawful in that it constituted a breach of contract.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1483\ri0\sb252\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 The cause of action on the main claim is thus an unusual one: it is based upon the allegation that in June 1971 Joel Melamed concluded a tacit contract with himself, he having acted therein in two different represen\-tative capacities, viz. as managing director of TMC, on behalf of TMC, on the one hand and as partner in the firm of Melamed and Hurwitz, on behalf of Melamed and Hurwitz, on the other hand. I shall later have some observations to make about such a cause of action. At this stage I would merely add that the plea puts in issue, \ul inter alia\ul0 , the making of such a tacit appointment, as also the two alternative claims.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li1483\fi0\ri0\sb626\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 At the trial the only witness to give evidence}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5364\fi0\ri0\sb482\sa0\tldot\tx7999 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 / was{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2254\margrsxn568\margtsxn1440\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li8546\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-11\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 20}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7\fi0\ri403\sb194\sa0\sl-727\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 was Joel Melamed. It appears that the other person vitally interested, Harry Galaun, had died on 7 September 1980, not long after the institution of these proceedings and about a year before the commencement of the trial. He was, therefore, not available to give evidence.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1469\ri0\sb115\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 In evidence-in-chief Melamed described his relationship with Galaun and the events leading up to the conclusion of the management contract. He stated that \expndtw20 prior\expndtw0  to the signing of \expndtw14 this\expndtw0  contract he had a dis-cussion with Galaun. He pointed out to Galaun that other township management companies were charging an establishment fee of between 10 and 1.5 per centum, but that he (meaning TMC) was prepared to agree to a fee of only 5 per centum since he anticipated that there would be "additional perks" to come from the establishment of the township, viz. the transfer costs which would be paid by various purchasers to Melamed and Hurwitz as conveyancers; and that "one of}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5350\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-720\slmult0\tldot\tx8287 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 / the{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2196\margrsxn360\margtsxn1440\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li8554\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-2\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 21}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb324\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 the conditions" for charging a reduced fee was that "all the transfers in the townships had to come to my firm". Galaun readily agreed to this. When the deeds of sale came to be prepared and printed, Melamed advised Galaun that, pursuant to their original arrangements, Melamed and Hurwitz was to be nominated therein as con\-veyancer for stands in the township. From the time that the management contract was signed Galaun's attitude was that Melamed was in charge of the townships and was to do every\-thing he thought fit in the interests of the townships. Said Melamed in evidence: "He (Galaun) relied upon me implicitly". He, Melamed, caused the relative clauses in the deeds of sale to contain a provision nominating Melamed and Hurwitz as conveyancer. In so nominating he acted on behalf of TMC and in accepting he acted on behalf of his firm. At all times Galaun knew that Melamed and Hurwitz was nominated to attend to the transfer of stands in the townships,}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5350\fi0\ri0\sb7\sa0\sl-720\slmult0\tldot\tx9346 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 / firstly{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2221\margrsxn746\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li8561\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-14\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 22}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li22\fi0\ri0\sb324\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 firstly because of the initial discussions between Melamed and himself, secondly because of the discussion regarding the drawing up of the deeds of sale and thirdly because he accepted and signed each deed of sale.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li7\fi1483\ri295\sb245\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 Melamed then proceeded in evidence-in-chief to describe the termination of the management contract, the subsequent disputes and correspondence between the parties and the basis of the damages claim. (At that stage the agreement to \expndtw15 limit\expndtw0  the issues to that of liability had not been reached.) I shall refer later to some of the evi\-dence given by Melamed under cross-examination.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1490\ri0\sb230\sa0\sl-727\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 In his judgment, the trial Judge focused attention on Melamed's evidence to the effect that prior to the con\-clusion of the management contract he arrived at an express oral agreement \expndtw17 with\expndtw0  Galaun that Me Lamed and Hurwitz would attend to the transfer of all the stands in the townships.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5357\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-727\slmult0\tldot\tx8438 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-4\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 / He\expndtw0 {\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2161\margrsxn475\margtsxn1278\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li8554\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-6\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 23}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb202\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 He held that this was an aspect of Melamed's evidence which did not impress him, particularly as there had been no prior mention of such an agreement, either in the motion proceedings or in the pleadings in the instant case. He felt constrained to find that Melamed did not enter into such an express agreement with Galaun prior to the signing of the manage\-ment contract. The learned Judge pointed to certain proba\-bilities "which may be argued in favour of Melamed's version", but concluded that they were "equally consistent" with an approach on Melamed's part that the management contract was not revocable. He referred to certain other grounds upon which Melamed's evidence could be criticized (I shall elaborate upon these later) and in the end found that "very little, if any weight" could be attached to Melamed's evidence. The learned Judge concluded:}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li3118\fi-151\ri0\sb295\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 "He (Melamed) has not satisfied me as to the existence of any express agreement which Galaun entered into prior to the signing of Annexure "A".}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li3118\fi749\ri0\sb115\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 In the light of the aforegoing it also follows that the plaintiff has not}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5350\fi0\ri0\sb7\sa0\sl-360\slmult0\tldot\tx8734 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 / made{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2138\margrsxn648\margtsxn950\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li8575\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-2\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 24}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2419\fi0\ri1728\sb353\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 made out a case in respect of the alternative claim.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li2405\fi446\ri1051\sb122\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 In the result the plaintiff's claim and counter-claim (meaning alternative claim) in each case are dismissed with costs."}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1505\ri0\sb317\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 It seems to me, with respect, that in regard to the main claim the trial Judge failed to address himself to the real issues in the case, viz. (i) whether it had been es\-tablished that Melamed, in his capacity as managing direc\-tor of TMC, had concluded a tacit agreement with himself, in his capacity as partner in the firm of Melamed and Hurwitz, in terms whereof the firm was appointed to act as conveyancers for the transfer of all stands in the townships in question; and (ii) whether the cancellation of this appointment constituted a breach of contract in respect of which the firm of Melamed and Hurwitz was entitled to claim damages. I proceed now to consider these issues.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li1469\fi0\ri0\sb245\sa0\sl-727\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 At the outset it is necessary to say something}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-727\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 of the legal principles involved. The question whether a}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-727\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 person can, as representative of another, contract with}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5350\fi0\ri0\sb331\sa0\tldot\tx8431 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 / himself{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2258\margrsxn385\margtsxn1131\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li8554\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx8554 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-6\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 25}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7\fi0\ri0\sb209\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 himself, either in his personal capacity or as representative of a third person, is discussed in the title in LAWSA treating of Agency and Representation, written by Prof J C de Wet (see LAWSA, vol 1, par 107 and 108). Despite the contrary view expressed by Prof De Wet, I shall assume in favour of Melamed and Hurwitz that it was legally competent for Melamed, in his capacity as Managing Director of TMC, to make a contract with himself, in his other capacity as partner in the firm of Melamed and Hurwitz, in terms whereof the latter was appointed as conveyancer for all the erven in the townships.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1469\ri806\sb245\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 A novel feature of appellant's main cause of action is that Melamed is not only alleged to have con\-tracted with himself in two different capacities, but also to have done so tacitly. 1 know of no case \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f1\cchs0 \'97\hich\af0\dbch\af1\loch\f0\cchs0  and certainly none was quoted to us \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f1\cchs0 \'97\hich\af0\dbch\af1\loch\f0\cchs0  where such a cause of action has been considered by our courts.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li1469\fi0\ri0\sb504\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 As to tacit contracts in general, in \ul Standard Bank}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5357\fi0\ri0\sb490\sa0\tldot\tx8748 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw18\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 /of\expndtw0  {\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2344\margrsxn608\margtsxn1415\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7776\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-6\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 26}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li29\fi0\ri1296\sb194\sa0\sl-727\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\ul\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 of SA Ltd v Ocean Commodities Inc\ul0 , 1983 (1) SA 276 (AD) it was stated (at p 292 B - C):}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2203\fi0\ri0\sb511\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 "In order to establish a tacit contract it is necessary to show, by a preponderance of probabilities, unequivocal conduct which is capable of no other reasonable interpre\-tation than that the parties intended to, and did in fact, contract on the terms alleged. It must be proved that there was in fact \ul consensus\ul0  ad \ul idem\ul0 . (See generally \ul Festus v Worcester Municipality\ul0 , 1945 CPD 186 at 192-3; \ul City of Cape Town v Abelsohn's Estate\ul0 ,1947 (3) SA 315 (C) at 327-8; \ul Parsons v Langemann and Others\ul0 , 1948 (4) SA 258 (C) at 263; \ul Bremer Meulens (Edms) Bpk v Floros and Another\ul0 , a decision of this Court reported only in Prentice Hall, 1966 (1) A36; \ul Blaikie-Johnstone v Holliman, \ul0 1971 (4) SA 108 (D) at 119 B-E; \ul Big Dutchman (South Africa) (Pty) Ltd v Barclays National Bank Ltd,\ul0  1979 (3) SA 267 (W) at 281 E-F; \ul Muhlmann v Muhlmann\ul0 , 1981 (4) SA 632 (W) at 635 B-D.) "}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb310\sa0\sl-727\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 This is the traditional statement of the principle, as is borne out by the cases cited; and it was accepted as being correct by appellant's counsel. The correctness of this general formulation has nevertheless been questioned}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5198\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-727\slmult0\tldot\tx8287 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 / on{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2254\margrsxn417\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7798\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-2\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 27}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb202\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 on the ground that it would appear to indicate a higher standard of proof than that of preponderance of probabili\-ty as regard the drawing of inferences from proven facts (see Christie, \ul The Law of Contract in South Africa\ul0 , pp 58-61; cf also \ul Fiat SA v Kolbe Motors,\ul0  1975 (2) SA 129 (0), at p 140; \ul Plum v Mazista Ltd\ul0 , 1981 (3) SA 152 (AD), at pp 163-4; \ul Spes Bona Bank v Portals Water Treatment\ul0 , 1983 (1) SA 978 (AD), at p 981 A-D). In this connection it is stated that a court may hold that a tacit contract has been established where, by a process of inference, it con\-cludes that the most plausible probable conclusion from all the relevant proved facts and circumstances is that a contract came into existence (see \ul Plum\ul0 's case, supra, at pp 163-4). It may be that in the light of this the principle as quoted above from \ul Standard Bank of SA Ltd v Ocean Commodities Inc\ul0  (\ul supra\ul0 ) requires reformulation. In this regard, however, there is this point to be borne in mind. While}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5191\fi0\ri0\sb7\sa0\sl-720\slmult0\tldot\tx8143 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw29\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 /it\expndtw0 {\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2207\margrsxn889\margtsxn1249\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\qr\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-4\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 28}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb310\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 it is perfectly true that in finding facts or making inferences of fact in a civil case the court may, by balancing probabilities, select a conclusion which seems to be the more natural or plausible one from several con\-ceivable ones, even though that conclusion is not the only reasonable one, nevertheless it may be argued that the inference as to the conclusion of a tacit contract is partly, at any rate, a matter of law, involving questions of legal policy. It appears to be generally accepted that a term may not be tacitly imported into a contract unless the implication is a necessary one in the business sense to give efficacy to the contract (see Van den Berq \ul v Tenner\ul0 , 1975 (2) SA 268 (AD), at pp 276 H - 277 B and the cases there cited). By analogy it could be said that a tacit contract should not be inferred unless there was proved unequivocal conduct capable of no other reasonable interpretation than that the parties intended to, and did in fact, contract on the terms alleged. Be that as}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5357\fi0\ri0\sb7\sa0\sl-720\slmult0\tldot\tx8150 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw46\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 /it\expndtw0 {\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2409\margrsxn544\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7783\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-14\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 29}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li14\fi0\ri0\sb310\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 it may, this is not the occasion to resolve these problems. The point was not argued and, on the view I take of the facts, it is not necessary to decide what real difference, if any, there is between the viewpoints outlined above or to express a preference for one or the other.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1202\ri0\sb245\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 In the cases concerning tacit contracts which have hitherto come before our courts, there have always been at least two persons involved; and in order to decide whether a tacit contract arose the court has had regard to the conduct of both parties and the circumstances of the case generally. The general approach is an objective one. The subjective views of one or other of the persons involved as to the effect of his actions would not normally be re\-levant (cf. \ul Spes Bona Bank\ul0  case (\ul surpa\ul0 ), at p 985 B-H). I shall assume, in appellant's favour, that where there is only one person involved (as in this case) a tacit}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5198\fi0\ri0\sb353\sa0\tldot\tx8287 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 / contract{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2352\margrsxn911\margtsxn1440\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7790\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 30}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li14\fi0\ri0\sb209\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 contract may be inferred from \ul his\ul0  conduct and the general}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7\fi0\ri0\sb7\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 circumstances, but in such a case the court should, in my view, carefully scrutinize" his evidence in order to distinguish between statements of fact capable of objec\-tive assessment and subjective views as to the matter in issue.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1188\ri0\sb238\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Next I turn to the nature of the tacit contract alleged by Melamed and Hurwitz. According to the plead\-ings it consisted of an appointment of Melamed and Hurwitz by TMC (acting, as agent of the township owners, under the management contract) to act as conveyancers for the transfer of all stands in the proposed townships. The conveyance of title to land involves the preparation of a deed of transfer, which must be done by a practising conveyancer (see sec 15 of the Deeds Registries Act, 47 of 1937), and, after due scrutiny of the deed by a Deeds Office examiner, the execution thereof in the presence}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5213\fi0\ri0\sb7\sa0\sl-720\slmult0\tldot\tx7553 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw23\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 /of\expndtw0 {\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2203\margrsxn655\margtsxn1440\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li8532\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 31}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb317\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 of the Registrar by the owner of the land, or by a con\-veyancer authorized by power of attorney to act on behalf of the owner, and the attestation thereof by the Registrar (sec 20). The conveyancer appointed to prepare the necessary deed of transfer and to attend to the execution of the deed before the Registrar performs a juristic act on behalf of his client, viz. the passing of transfer. This is, therefore, an instance of representation in the technical sense of the term (see LAWSA, vol 1, par 101 et \ul seq\ul0 .). An act of representation needs to be authorized by the principal. Such authorization is usually con\-tained in a contract. In the present case the contract is the tacit one alleged by Melamed and Hurwitz. The first question which must now be considered is: did Melamed and Hurwitz succeed in proving the tacit appointment, or grant to it of an authority, to act as conveyancers for the transfer of all stands in the proposed townships?}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5364\fi0\ri0\sb619\sa0\tldot\tx8143 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 / I have{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2261\margrsxn864\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li8359\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 32}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1490\ri0\sb331\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 I have already outlined the evidence given by Melamed in chief. In it he did not refer directly to the tacit appointment alleged in the pleadings. In cross-examination, however, he was asked about this. He agreed that he did not, in his capacity as managing director of TMC, sit on one side of the desk and speak to himself, as partner in Melamed and Hurwitz, on the other side of the desk and formally appoint himself. He stated that it was a "tacit arrangement". When asked during his cross-examination on what conduct he relied to establish the tacit appointment, his evidence was somewhat confused. Initially he said that he relied on \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f1\cchs0 \'97}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li3118\fi-151\ri0\sb540\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 ".... the discussions with Galaun initially, on the time when the deed of sale was drawn and the discussions that I had with Galaun that Melamed and Hurwitz were to be nominated in all Deeds of Sale for the purpose of transfer."}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5350\fi0\ri0\sb648\sa0\tldot\tx8280 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw22\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs26 /It\expndtw0 {\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2200\margrsxn738\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\qr\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 33}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li22\fi0\ri403\sb317\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 It was pointed out to him by counsel that these discus\-sions amounted to express, not tacit, arrangements. To which he replied that the discussions with Galaun were express, "but the acceptance by Melamed and Hur-witz was tacit with myself". Shortly thereafter he conceded that the agreement with Galaun was wholly an express one. When taxed with the question as to why he had not relied on this express agreement with Galaun in his pleadings, Melamed stated \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f1\cchs0 \'97}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2542\fi-130\ri806\sb518\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 "But I'm saying that the second stage was when the deeds of Sale were drawn, that was when TMC appointed Melamed and Hurwitz, that was the tacit con\-tract which was to the knowledge and approval of Galaun".}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb324\sa0\sl-727\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Asked whether he relied simply on conduct for this appoint\-ment, Melamed stated \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f1\cchs0 \'97}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5364\fi0\ri0\sb619\sa0\tldot\tx7690 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 / "No, I{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2236\margrsxn875\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\qr\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 34}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2513\fi-137\ri1210\sb612\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 "No, I don't rely on conduct. I rely on the arrangements between myself representing TMC and my\-self representing Melamed &}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2513\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Hurwitz".}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7\fi0\ri403\sb302\sa0\sl-727\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Reminded that it had been pleaded that the appointment was made tacitly and that this meant reliance on some form of conduct, Melamed eventually stated \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f1\cchs0 \'97}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2520\fi-144\ri1210\sb533\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 "What happened was I instructed that all the Deeds of Sale had to be prepared on the basis that Melamed and Hurwitz were nomi\-nated as the conveyancers for the entire township."}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7\fi0\ri0\sb324\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 He stated further that the tacit agreement was entered into at the time the deeds of sale were drawn. This occurred in or about May 1971. His evidence proceeded \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f1\cchs0 \'97}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2520\fi-130\ri0\sb1015\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 "All right, then what took place on the date in May when you say the contract was entered into?-- The Deeds of Sale were drawn and my firm was nominated}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5350\fi0\ri0\sb346\sa0\tldot\tx8136 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 / as{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2168\margrsxn950\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\qr\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 35}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2376\fi0\ri0\sb713\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 as the conveyancer on all the Deeds of}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2362\fi0\ri0\sb22\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Sale and I tacitly accepted the appoint\-ment.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2376\fi605\ri0\sb130\sa0\sl-353\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 So all that you rely on is the Deed of Sale?\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f1\cchs0 \'97\hich\af0\dbch\af1\loch\f0\cchs0  And the discussion with Galaun at the time."}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb317\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Later this version of the tacit appointment was further elaborated as follows:}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2369\fi598\ri864\sb533\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 "But let me put it to you then, we have the position that as far as TMC is concerned we have no formal document, no formal appointment, it's simply one by conduct?\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f1\cchs0 \'97\hich\af0\dbch\af1\loch\f0\cchs0  That is correct.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2362\fi576\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 And the only conduct you rely on is the fact that you as Joel Melamed & Hurwitz or you as TMC, I'm not sure which, had forms printed?-- No, the conduct was when I had the forms printed for the purposes of the sale, I nominated my firm with the intention that my firm should do the totality of transfers in the townships.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2369\fi734\ri0\sb122\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 The only issue is the totality, and that's the only bit we're quibbling about, where's the totality come from?--}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5342\fi0\ri0\sb202\sa0\tldot\tx7675 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 / The{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2207\margrsxn889\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\qr\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 36}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2369\fi0\ri432\sb605\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 The totality comes from the basis that I never sat down with myself, Mr Plewman, and had a meeting with myself to draw a contract in which I said 'I, TMC, am appointing Melamed & Hurwitz to do all the trans\-fers in the township'. I do the Deeds of Sale on the understanding with myself that Melamed & Hurwitz were nominated as the conveyancers for the entire township."}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri432\sb317\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Here, for the first time, Melamed mentioned "the under\-standing with myself that Melamed and Hurwitz were nominated as the conveyancers for the entire township". Thereafter, in his evidence, Melamed referred several times to this understanding or intention on his part that Melamed and Hurwitz would do all the transfers in the townships. He agreed that there was no ex\-ternal manifestation of this understanding or inten\-tion.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5364\fi0\ri0\sb396\sa0\tldot\tx7560 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw29\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 /It\expndtw0 {\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2222\margrsxn910\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\qr\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-13\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 37}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1483\ri403\sb310\sa0\sl-727\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 It is thus evident that in order to establish the alleged tacit contract Melamed relied (a) partly on overt conduct and circumstances and (b) partly on an "understanding" with himself, which consisted merely of the thoughts which passed through his mind and had no outward manifestation. I shall assume in appellant's favour that (b) above can form the basis of a tacit contract.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1483\ri403\sb216\sa0\sl-727\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 In assessing the cogency of this evidence as to a tacit contract, there are a number of factors to be taken into account. Firstly, there are the probabilities. I have no doubt that Melamed did, at some stage, discuss with Galaun the conveyancing work to be done in connection with the transfer of erven in the townships and that Galaun was then satisfied to have the work done by Melamed and Hurwitz.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5350\fi0\ri0\sb7\sa0\sl-727\slmult0\tldot\tx7682 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw24\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs26 /It\expndtw0 {\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2178\margrsxn1278\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb9713\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 38}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 It seems probable, too, that Galaun was aware of the fact that in the \ul pro forma\ul0  deeds of sale Melamed and Hurwitz had been nominated as conveyancer and that until the termination of the firm's appointment in mid-1979 it was in fact doing the conveyancing work relating to the townships. I also accept that it was at all times Melamed's intention that his firm should do all the conveyancing work in the townships; that this work was important to his firm; and that, because of the peculiar relationship between TMC and Melamed and Hur\-witz, TMC, in the anticipation that Melamed and Hurwitz would do the conveyancing work, accepted a lower-than-usual establishment fee. But for two important factors, these circumstances might be regarded as probabilities favouring the conclusion of the tacit agreement alleged by Melamed and Hurwitz.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5364\fi0\ri0\sb634\sa0\tldot\tx7553 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 / The{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2181\margrsxn908\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\qr\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-1\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 39}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1483\ri0\sb338\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 The first factor is Melamed's belief, at all times until the delivery of judgment in the application proceedings, that the appointment of TMC as agent under the management contract was an appointment in \ul rem suam \ul0 and irrevocable at the instance of the township owners. Melamed deposed to this belief on a number of occasions during his evidence. In his mind this meant that for the entire life of each of the townships TMC's appointment could not be revoked and that, inas\-much as TMC had the right (under clause 8) to appoint attorneys to attend, \ul inter alia\ul0 , to the transfer of stands in the townships, Melamed and Hurwitz would do the to\-tality of transfers in the townships. In the circum\-stances, from Melamed's viewpoint, it would not have been necessary for him to conclude, with himself, a tacit agreement appointing Melamed and Hurwitz}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5378\fi0\ri0\sb7\sa0\sl-720\slmult0\tldot\tx8158 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 / conveyancers{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2240\margrsxn871\margtsxn1440\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li8510\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx8510 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 40}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri403\sb310\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 conveyancers for all the erven in the townships. Because of the assumed irrevocability of the manage\-ment contract, there was no need to secure the future position of Melamed and Hurwitz as convey\-ancers. Nor was there any reason why the future position of Melamed and Hurwitz as conveyancers should, at the time of the preparation of the deeds of sale or at any other relevant time, have engaged the thoughts or aroused the concerns of Melamed. As far as he was concerned, the management contract was irrevocable and, therefore, the position of Melamed and Hurwitz unassailable; and that was the end of the matter. That this in fact was Melamed's general thinking is borne out by the fact that no formal document appointing Melamed and Hurwitz as conveyancers was ever drawn up. Melamed was cross-examined about this. He said that a formal document would have been}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5357\fi0\ri0\sb14\sa0\sl-720\slmult0\tldot\tx7546 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 / "totally{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2228\margrsxn1026\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\qr\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-1\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 41}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li14\fi0\ri806\sb310\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 "totally unnecessary". He had the management con\-tract which he considered to be irrevocable, and under that management contract he could make the appointment, as he stated, "during the life of the management contract".}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1476\ri403\sb259\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 The second factor is the fact that Melamed and Galaun, who directed the affairs of Cleveland and Vomer, were very close personal friends and had been such for some years prior to the alleged tacit appoint\-ment in May 1971. Because of this close personal relationship, it was, to use Melamed's own words, "unthinkable" that Galaun would appoint any attorneys other than Melamed and Hurwitz to do the conveyancing work relating to the townships. In fact, in reply to certain questions by the Court about this use of the word "unthinkable" Melamed said \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f1\cchs0 \'97}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5364\fi0\ri0\sb634\sa0\tldot\tx7848 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 /"... There{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2196\margrsxn914\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\qr\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-9\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 42}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2376\fi-144\ri864\sb612\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 "... There was no question that we have been awarded the contract, there was no question of that, there was no question in the on\-going scene as existed that Galaun would have appointed anybody else.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2376\fi605\ri1296\sb122\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 It never crossed your mind?--Correct M'lord."}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li14\fi0\ri864\sb317\sa0\sl-727\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 This, therefore, constitutes another reason why it would have been unnecessary for Melamed to have con\-cluded the alleged tacit contract with himself and why it is unlikely that Melamed would have given thought to doing so.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1505\ri864\sb216\sa0\sl-727\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 In my view, these two factors favour the probability that Melamed, secure in the knowledge that the management contract was irrevocable and}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri1296\sb0\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 that, in any event, it was unthinkable that his good friend Galaun would want any firm other than}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5364\fi0\ri0\sb598\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 / Melamed and....}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2221\margrsxn889\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\qr\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-13\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 43}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri432\sb317\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 Melamed and Hurwitz to do the conveyancing work, would not have given any thought to a general appointment of Melamed and Hurwitz as conveyan\-cers, but would merely have proceeded on an ad \ul hoc \ul0 basis to deal with each transfer and in each case to give the necessary instructions to, and sign the required power of attorney in favour of, Melamed and Hurwitz. And, moreover, this was why no formal document was executed appointing Melamed and Hurwitz as conveyancers to attend to the transfer of all stands in the townships. Had Melamed adverted to the need for such an appointment it seems likely, in view of the importance of the matter, that there would have been some written record thereof}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5342\fi0\ri0\sb713\sa0\tldot\tx7373 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 / or{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2146\margrsxn936\margtsxn1440\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li8554\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx8554 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 44}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li29\fi0\ri432\sb324\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 or some other outward and unequivocal manifestation of his intentions. After all, he himself might die and with his death all proof of this appointment would be obliterated.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1476\ri0\sb245\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 As I have indicated, Melamed relied very much upon the nomination of Melamed and Hurwitz in the \ul pro forma \ul0 deeds of sale as constituting conduct from which a tacit contract in the terms alleged should be inferred. To my mind, this conduct is equivocal. It is at least equally consistent with a mere intention or general expectation on Melamed's part, founded on the irrevoca\-bility of the management contract, that Melamed and Hurwitz would do all the conveyancing in connection with the townships. Here a sharp distinction must be drawn between a general intention that the firm should do all this conveyancing and an intention to conclude a contract whereby the firm was appointed to do such conveyancing.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5364\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-720\slmult0\tldot\tx8597 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 / Turning{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn1923\margrsxn575\margtsxn1224\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7783\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-7\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 45}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1202\ri0\sb317\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 Turning more specifically to the merits of Melamed's evidence, the trial Judge, as 1 have recounted, held that very little, if any, weight could be attached thereto. This adverse credibility finding was based (i) on Melamed's evidence of an express agreement with Galaun prior to the signing of the management contract, which evidence DE VILLIERS J rejected mainly for the reasons that I have already indicated; (ii) on Melamed's "uncertainty" under cross-examination as to whether he ever had such an express agreement with Galaun; and (iii) inconsistency in Melamed's evidence as to the warmth of his friendship with Galaun. I do not propose to discuss these grounds of criticism in detail. As to (i), I think that it is some\-what strange that Melamed should not have mentioned this express agreement in the motion proceedings and should not have relied thereon, as an alternative cause of action, in the present case, but I am not disposed to give as much weight to this factor as the trial Judge did. Melamed}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5213\fi0\ri0\sb7\sa0\sl-720\slmult0\tldot\tx8302 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 / evidently{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2355\margrsxn727\margtsxn1195\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7790\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-7\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 46}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb324\sa0\sl-727\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 evidently took the view that after the conclusion of the management contract only TMC had the right to make an appointment of conveyancers. And, in any event, as I have already indicated, it seems probable that Melamed would at least have told Galaun at some stage that the conveyancing work was to be done by Melamed and Hurwitz and that Galaun would have acquiesced therein. As to (ii) above, the trial Judge quoted in his judgment the relevant passage from the cross-examination of Melamed. In the course of this Melamed did say: "I did not have an express agreement with Mr Galaun, I advised Mr Galaun of what was taking place". This is contradictory of his earlier evi\-dence and is confusing, but the answer may be that Melamed was endeavouring to explain at this stage that only TMC had the right under the management contract to make an appointment. As to (iii) above, this criticism seems to be fully justified: there is a contradiction in Melamed's evidence on this point.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5227\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-727\slmult0\tldot\tx8330 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw23\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 /To\expndtw0  {\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2139\margrsxn360\margtsxn1397\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7805\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-11\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 47}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li29\fi1195\ri0\sb173\sa0\sl-727\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 To these criticisms I would add the following. Melamed's evidence on the tacit contract (I have earlier referred to this in more detail) is, in my opinion, confused and unconvincing. I gain the impression that he was to a large extent reconstructing. He partly conceded this:}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2225\fi-122\ri432\sb533\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 "So what has happened throughout, is that you have gone back and looked at the events and said now what events would it have been that would have provided this particular piece of the jig-saw puzzle?\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f1\cchs0 \'97 \hich\af0\dbch\af1\loch\f0\cchs0 Correct. It is partially a reconstruction, I concede that."}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb310\sa0\sl-727\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 Indeed, faulty reconstruction seems to have been the cause of the incorrect date initially pleaded for the conclusion of the tacit contract, viz June 1971 (instead of May 1971). When cross-examined about this Melamed explained that two dates had been "transposed" by counsel. Seeing that the other date referred to was February/March 1971 (not May 1971), that it appears in the plaintiff's particulars of claim (drawn on 18 July 1980), whereas the other date (June 1971) appears}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5213\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-727\slmult0\tldot\tx8755 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 / in{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2286\margrsxn558\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7790\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 48}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li22\fi0\ri403\sb310\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 in the further particulars thereto (drawn on 17 October 1980) and that Melamed, an experienced attorney, approved the pleadings, I have some difficulty in accepting this explanation.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1195\ri0\sb252\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 The trial Judge made no express finding on de\-meanour. A reading of the recorded evidence indicates, to my mind, a tendency on Melamed's part to evade questions and to fence with counsel. I quote one of several examples. Melamed was asked whether there had been any oral acceptance by him of the alleged \ul stipulatio alteri\ul0  when each deed of sale was signed by Galaun. It had been originally alleged in the pleadings that such acceptance had been "oral, alternatively, in writing". During the course of a lengthy cross-examination on this point, he agreed that he did not say to Galaun "I'm accepting the \ul stipulatio\ul0 " each time a deed was signed. The evidence continues:}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5047\fi0\ri0\sb634\sa0\tldot\tx7236 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 /"We {\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2423\margrsxn400\margtsxn1123\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7754\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 49}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2686\fi0\ri0\sb691\sa0\tlhyph\tx8950 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 "We agree to that - that didn't happen.{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qc\li0\fi0\ri58\sb94\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Right, no that couldn't happen.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2218\fi583\ri432\sb36\sa0\sl-360\slmult0\tldot\tx3204 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Right, so there wasn't an oral accep\-\line tance?\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f1\cchs0 \'97\hich\af0\dbch\af1\loch\f0\cchs0  No, there was not an oral\line acceptance in that form, but I regarded\line my{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2218\fi583\ri432\sb0\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 There wasn't an oral acceptance in any form, Mr Melamed.-- Right, in that form there was - there was the acceptance in my mind when Galaun signed the Deed of Sale, that I accepted.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2232\fi576\ri432\sb0\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Mr Melamed, with due respect, I'm asking about an oral acceptance. Are we agreed there was no oral acceptance?\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f1\cchs0 \'97\hich\af0\dbch\af1\loch\f0\cchs0  No, there was no oral acceptance in that form.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2232\fi576\ri432\sb7\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 But there was no oral acceptance at all, agreed?\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f1\cchs0 \'97\hich\af0\dbch\af1\loch\f0\cchs0  I did not say to myself 'I accept the stipulatio', right.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2232\fi590\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Is the answer there was no oral acceptance at all?\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f1\cchs0 \'97\hich\af0\dbch\af1\loch\f0\cchs0  In that form, no.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2225\fi576\ri432\sb0\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Leave out the words 'in that form', was there no oral acceptance?\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f1\cchs0 \'97\hich\af0\dbch\af1\loch\f0\cchs0  There was no oral acceptance, I'll acknowledge that."}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1181\ri432\sb317\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Having considered all the evidence in the light of the aforegoing, I am not satisfied, despite the absence of countervailing evidence, that a tacit contract on the terms alleged by Melamed and Hurwitz came into being. In brief my reasons are that the objective conduct re\-lied upon, viz. the printing of the \ul pro forma\ul0  deed of}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5220\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-720\slmult0\tldot\tx8014 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 / sale{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2225\margrsxn734\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li8539\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx8539 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 50}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7\fi0\ri864\sb202\sa0\sl-727\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 sale in which Melamed and Hurwitz is nominated as con\-veyancer, is, in all the circumstances, equivocal. Melamed's statement that he -}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2383\fi-137\ri432\sb526\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 "nominated (his) firm with the intention that (his) firm should do the totality of transfers in the townships"}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb317\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 (and similar statements elsewhere in his evidence) is, in my view, not sufficient to carry the day. Having regard to the evidence of Melamed as a whole, the state\-ment smacks of reconstruction; and, moreover, it is not clear that in giving this evidence Melamed was distinguish\-ing in his own mind a general intention that his firm should do the "totality of the transfers" and an intention to con\-clude a contract whereby his firm was appointed to do this work. The probabilities do not support the alleged tacit contract. On the contrary, if anything, the probabilities are adverse to the appellant's case.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5364\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-720\slmult0\tldot\tx7848 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 / This{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2218\margrsxn879\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\qr\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-4\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 51}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1469\ri0\sb209\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 This conclusion renders unnecessary a considera\-tion of the second main issue, viz. whether the cancella\-tion of the alleged tacit appointment amounted to a breach of contract entitling Melamed and Hurwitz to claim damages. This would depend on whether or not the appointment was irrevocable, in the sense that the premature revocation or cancellation thereof constituted a breach of contract and exposed the principal to a claim for damages at the suit of Melamed and Hurwitz. This appears to be a controversial branch of the law (see e.g. \ul Price Bros and Barnes Ltd v Snyman\ul0 , 1936 TPD 332, at p 338; \ul Cape Dairy and General Livestock Auctioneers v Badenhorst\ul0 , 1937 TPD 282, at p 287; De Villiers and Macintosh, \ul The Law of Agency in South Africa\ul0 , 3rd ed., pp 405 et seq, 614 et \ul seq\ul0 ; compare Kerr, T\ul he Law of Agency\ul0 , 2nd ed., p 194; De Wet and Yeats,\ul Kontraktereg en Handelsreg\ul0 , 4th ed., p 343; LAWSA, vol 17, par. 16(g); and as to the revocation of a}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5357\fi0\ri0\sb7\sa0\sl-720\slmult0\tldot\tx8280 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 / general{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2171\margrsxn925\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li8554\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx8554 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-4\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 52}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri403\sb324\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 general retainer given to an attorney, see the English case of \ul J H Milner and Son v Percy Bilton Ltd\ul0 , [1966] 2 All ER 894). The point was not argued before us. In all the circumstances I do not propose to do more than say that it is by no means clear to me that, even if plaintiff had established the tacit con\-tract alleged, it would have been entitled to damages by reason of the termination of its appointment as conveyancer.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7\fi1490\ri0\sb238\sa0\sl-727\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 For these reasons, I have come to the conclu\-sion that the appellant did not establish the tacit contract pleaded by it and that appellant's main claim was, therefore, correctly dismissed by the Court \ul a quo\ul0 .}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1490\ri0\sb223\sa0\sl-734\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 The two alternative claims were not strenuously pressed before us. The first alternative pleaded refers}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5364\fi0\ri0\sb367\sa0\tldot\tx8302 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 / to{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2247\margrsxn1023\margtsxn1440\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li8381\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx8381 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-4\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 53}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li22\fi0\ri0\sb331\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 to the oral adoption, confirmation or ratification by Galaun of the tacit appointment of Melamed and Hurwitz by TMC. I assume that this alternative was inserted to cover the situation should it have been held that TMC did not have authority to make such an appointment. Since, however, TMC's authority in this regard was not disputed and as 1 have held that a tacit appointment was not esta\-blished, this alternative claim becomes irrelevant.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1469\ri0\sb245\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 The second alternative claim was based upon the averment that the "appointment" of Melamed and Hurwitz as conveyancer in each signed deed of sale constituted a stipulation for the benefit of Melamed and Hurwitz, which stipulation the latter had in each case accepted. With regard to the contract for the benefit of a third party, or \ul stipulatio alteri\ul0  as it is sometimes known, it was stated by SCHREINER JA in \ul Crookes NO and Another v Watson and Others\ul0 , 1956 (1) SA 277 (AD), at p 291 B - F:}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5206\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-720\slmult0\tldot\tx6638 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-6\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 /"\expndtw0 {\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab } in the}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2369\margrsxn864\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li8266\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx8266 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 54}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2282\fi0\ri0\sb626\sa0\sl-360\slmult0\tldot\tx3233 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 "{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab } in the legal sense, which alone}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2254\fi0\ri403\sb0\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 is here relevant, what is not very ap\-propriately styled a contract for the benefit of a third person is not simply a contract designed to benefit a third person; it is a contract between two persons that is designed to enable a third person to come in as a party to a contract with one of the other two (\ul cf Jankelow v Binder, Gering and Co\ul0 .,}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2254\fi0\ri0\sb7\sa0\sl-360\slmult0\tldot\tx5926 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 1927 TPD 364) {\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab } the typical}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2232\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 contract for the benefit of a third person is one where A and B make a contract in order that C may be enabled, by notifying A, to become a party to a contract between himself and A. What contractual rights exist between A and B pending acceptance by C and how far after such acceptance it is still possible for contractual relations between A and B to persist are matters on which differen\-ces of opinion are possible; but broadly speaking the idea of such transactions is that B drops out when C accepts and thenceforward it is A and C who are bound to each other."}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li14\fi0\ri0\sb331\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Although this was a minority judgment (concurred in by FAGAN JA), there is nothing inconsistent therewith in the}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5213\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-720\slmult0\tldot\tx8302 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 / majority{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2362\margrsxn900\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\qr\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-9\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 55}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb194\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 majority judgments and it has generally been regarded as an authoritative statement of the law (see eg \ul George Ruggier and Co v Brook\ul0 , 1966 (1) SA 17 (N) at p 23 and the cases there cited; \ul Comm\ul0 er\ul cial and Industrial Holdings (Pty) Ltd v Braamfontein Industrial Sites (Pty) Ltd\ul0 , 1969 (1) SA 479 (T), at p 493 E - H; \ul Protea Holdings and Another v Herzberg and Another\ul0 , 1982 (4) SA 773 (c), at p 779 G - H). Further, as was pointed out in the \ul George Ruggier\ul0  case (\ul supra\ul0 , at p 23 H) \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f1\cchs0 \'97}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2383\fi-130\ri432\sb533\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 "It is entirely a question whether there is an intention that the third party can, by adoption of the promise, become a party to the contract in which it is embodied".}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7\fi1310\ri0\sb310\sa0\sl-727\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 I do not think that the relevant provisions of the deeds of sale constituted stipulations for the benefit of a third party (Melamed and Hurwitz) in the above-described sense. To demonstrate this I shall refer}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5220\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-727\slmult0\tldot\tx7999 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw43\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 /to\expndtw0 {\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2437\margrsxn738\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li8352\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx8352 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-23\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs26 56}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb302\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 to the Cleveland contract; but my remarks are equally applicable to the Vomer contract, which is in simi\-lar terms. The relevant portion of the Cleveland contract, clause 10, which is headed "Transfer", reads as follows:}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2203\fi0\ri0\sb518\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 "The Purchaser shall pay the costs of this Deed of Sale and all costs of and incidental to transfer of the property including stamp and transfer duty. Transfer of the property shall be passed to the PURCHASER by the SELLER'S Con\-veyancers, JOEL MELAMED & HURWITZ, as soon as the full purchase price plus interest and \expndtw13 all\expndtw0  other amounts, charges and costs payable in terms hereof, have been paid, provided that the PURCHASER acknowledges that he is aware that the SELLER cannot, at law, transfer the property to the PURCHASER until proclamation of the Township and until transfer has been registered of such erven as are required to be transferred to the State or to the Provincial or Local Authorities concerned, as may be required by the conditions of establish\-ment of the said Township."}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5191\fi0\ri0\sb842\sa0\tldot\tx8734 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 /I {\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2240\margrsxn1022\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb9734\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 57}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 I do not think that there can be read into this provision an intention on the part of the parties to the contract, viz Cleveland and the purchaser, to confer upon Melamed and Hurwitz the benefit of being appointed to do the necessary conveyancing work and an intention that Melamed and Hurwitz could, by accepting this "benefit" become a party to the contract. The purpose of clause 10 is to regulate the passing of transfer as between seller and purchaser and it makes certain provisions in that regard. The clause contains no express promise in favour of Melamed and Hurwitz and no express benefit is conferred upon that firm. Melamed and Hurwitz are merely mentioned incidentally in connection with the stipulation that transfer shall be passed by the seller's conveyancer. No doubt it was considered convenient that the purchaser should know who the seller's conveyancer was. I think}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5364\fi0\ri0\sb598\sa0\tldot\tx8446 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 / that{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2236\margrsxn860\margtsxn1440\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li8554\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx8554 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-4\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 58}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li14\fi0\ri432\sb209\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 that both parties would have been surprised to be told that in agreeing to clause 10 they were not only con\-ferring this "benefit" on Melamed and Hurwitz but also permitting the latter, by acceptance, to come in as a party to the contract.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1447\ri0\sb238\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 The uncertainty and confusion surrounding appel\-lant's case on the question of acceptance reinforce, I \expndtw10 think,\expndtw0  the point that this clause 10 was never intended to contain a contract for the benefit of a \expndtw14 third\expndtw0  party. As 1 have indicated, it was pleaded originally that the benefit was accepted in each case \expndtw19 orally\expndtw0  or, alternatively, in writing. In cross-examination, after a certain amount of skirmishing (partly illustrated by one of the passages from his evidence quoted above), Me Lamed conceded that the alleged acceptance was neither oral nor in \expndtw12 writing,\expndtw0  but tacit. He was asked, "Tacitly by what conduct?", to which he replied:}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5364\fi0\ri0\sb7\sa0\sl-720\slmult0\tldot\tx7704 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 / "By{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2254\margrsxn849\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\qr\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-1\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 59}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2376\fi0\ri403\sb864\sa0\sl-360\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 "By my conduct in asking Galaun to sign the deeds of sale and accepting it tacitly in my own mind there and then."}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li14\fi0\ri0\sb317\sa0\sl-720\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Further cross-examination revealed that he was not present every time that a deed of sale was signed. This also introduces problems in regard to the proof of acceptance.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi1483\ri403\sb238\sa0\sl-727\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 In general, I do not think that appellant established its case in regard to the alternative claim based upon an alleged \ul stipulatio\ul0  alteri.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7\fi1476\ri0\sb230\sa0\sl-734\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 The appeals are accordingly dismissed with costs, which shall include the costs of two counsel.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li4896\fi0\ri0\sb1447\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 M M CORBETT}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb360\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 KOTZE JA)}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7\fi0\ri0\sb425\sa0\sl-302\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-56\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs40 TREVGORE JA) CONCUR.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7\fi0\ri5242\sb0\sa0\sl-302\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-56\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs40 SMUTS AJA \expndtw0\fs22 GROSSKOPF AJA)}\par }